The '''Argentina national football team''',{{efn|group=upper-alpha|{{langx|es|Selección de fútbol de Argentina}}}} nicknamed '''''la Albiceleste''''',&hairsp;{{efn|group=upper-alpha|English: ''The White and Sky Blue''}} represents [[Argentina]] in men's international [[Association football|football]] and is administered by the [[Argentine Football Association]], the governing body of [[football in Argentina]]. It has been a member of [[FIFA]] since 1912 and was a founding member of [[CONMEBOL]] in 1916. It was also a member of [[Panamerican Championship#Panamerican Football Confederation|PFC]], the unified confederation of the Americas, from 1946 to 1961. Argentina is the current FIFA World Cup champion, having won the most recent World Cup in [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]. The team previously won the World Cup in [[1978 FIFA World Cup final|1978]] and [[1986 FIFA World Cup final|1986]], and has appeared in the World Cup [[List of FIFA World Cup finals|final]] a total of six times.  

Argentina has won the [[Copa América]] a record 16 times, most recently in [[2024 Copa América|2024]]. With victories in [[1945 South American Championship|1945]], [[1946 South American Championship|1946]] and [[1947 South American Championship|1947]], it is the only nation to win the tournament three consecutive times. Argentina won the [[Panamerican Championship]] in [[1960 Panamerican Championship|1960]], the [[1992 King Fahd Cup|inaugural FIFA Confederations Cup]] in 1992, and the [[CONMEBOL–UEFA Cup of Champions]] in [[1993 Artemio Franchi Cup|1993]] and [[2022 Finalissima|2022]]. Argentina holds the record for most official international titles, with 23.{{efn|group=upper-alpha|Attributed to multiple references:<ref>{{Cite web |date=14 July 2024 |title=Tras la conquista de Argentina en la Copa América, así quedó la tabla histórica de títulos de las selecciones del mundo |url=https://www.infobae.com/deportes/2024/07/14/asi-esta-la-tabla-historica-de-las-selecciones-con-mas-titulos-en-el-mundo-en-la-previa-a-las-finales-de-la-copa-america-y-la-eurocopa/ |access-date=12 August 2024 |website=infobae |language=es-ES}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Ritchie |first=Calum |date=1 June 2024 |title=The 10 most successful nations in football history ranked by major trophies won |url=https://www.givemesport.com/most-successful-nations-in-football-history-by-major-trophies-won/ |access-date=12 August 2024 |website=GiveMeSport |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Top five nations with most major international football trophies |url=https://khelnow.com/football/2023-08-world-football-most-international-football-trophies |access-date=12 August 2024 |website=Khel Now |language=en-us}}</ref>}} Argentina players have won the [[FIFA World Cup awards#Golden Ball|FIFA World Cup Golden Ball]] three times: [[Diego Maradona]] in 1986, and [[Lionel Messi]] in [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]] and 2022. Messi has the most appearances for the team (198) and has scored the most goals (116). {{As of|2026|5|5}}, Argentina ranks 3rd in the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking]]. Argentina is known for having rivalries with [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]], [[England national football team|England]], [[France national football team|France]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Argentina-Francia, una historia de rivalidades y partidos para siempre|url=https://www.fifa.com/es/tournaments/olympicgames/paris2024/mens/articles/historial-argentina-francia-partidos-mundiales-torneos-resultados|date=30 July 2024|access-date=4 August 2024}}</ref> [[Germany national football team|Germany]], the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] and [[Uruguay national football team|Uruguay]].